{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Seam map: environment seam (real filesystem watcher recursion and OS-emitted events for nested paths). A unit/integration fake that directly invokes callbacks can miss real watcher configuration or platform recursion failures (MOCK-HIDE). Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow are disqualified because behavior text is purely filesystem/event handling with no AI/model step.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temporary watched directory, create a nested subdirectory, write a file inside it, and assert exactly one transformed output appears in the output directory for that nested file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Seam map: local function/object seam (path+time-window dedup decision). The failure is core dedup state/timing logic and can be reproduced with a fake clock and in-memory state; real OS/network/subprocess are not required. Rejection gate: Integration/System are disqualified by behavior text focusing on 'same file path within a configurable time window' rather than watcher/OS behavior.","test_description":"Call the dedup component twice for the same canonical path within the configured window using a controlled clock; assert first call is accepted and second is rejected, then advance time past window and assert acceptance again.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.26,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Seam map: environment seam (real OS filesystem event burst behavior). MOCK-MISS and MOCK-HIDE both apply: synthetic single-event mocks often pass while real platforms emit duplicate/sequence variants (rename/change/chmod), which is the failure boundary. Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow disqualified because no model-dependent correctness is involved.","test_description":"Run the daemon with a real watch directory, perform a write pattern known to trigger multiple events on the target OS (e.g., temp-write then rename), and assert exactly one processing result/output record for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Seam map: environment seam (live OS directory deletion/recreation and watcher re-subscription). This failure appears at runtime interaction with real watcher backends; in-process mocks can hide missed reattach logic or backend edge cases. Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow disqualified by behavior text being strictly daemon+filesystem lifecycle.","test_description":"Start daemon watching a real directory, delete that directory, recreate it at the same path while daemon stays running, then add a new file and assert it is processed successfully without restarting the process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Seam map: environment seam (real concurrent arrivals plus filesystem timestamp retrieval/resolution) crossing into queue ordering module seam. Integration could test sorting in isolation, but real failure risk is timestamp/event ordering under actual filesystem behavior; fakes may not reproduce ties/resolution quirks (MOCK-HIDE). Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow disqualified because no AI/model output is part of correctness.","test_description":"Create multiple files nearly simultaneously in the real watched directory, capture their filesystem creation timestamps as seen by the daemon, and assert processing completion order matches the daemon’s specified timestamp ordering rule.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.66,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Seam map: environment seam (real partial writes, event timing, and readiness detection). The bug depends on true write-in-progress behavior; mocked file-readiness checks often pass and hide races. Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow disqualified since behavior text concerns filesystem write completion semantics only.","test_description":"Begin writing a large file in chunks to the watched directory while keeping the write stream open, confirm daemon does not process during active writes, then close the stream and assert processing occurs once after completion.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.89,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
